  <ability>
    <abilitytitle>Charge</abilitytitle>
    <abilityid>physical.charge</abilityid>
    <abilityclass>Melee</abilityclass>
    <keywords><physical/></keywords>
    <abilityattrmodifiers><attr>Willpower</attr></abilityattrmodifiers>
    <abilitydescription>
      <p>
        The Charge ability allows the character to move twice their movement rate
        in the direction of an enemy and then make an additional melee attack.
        A character cannot Charge and enemy who is within their movement range, there
        is not enough time.  If the character fails to charge they realize their foolishness
        half way to the  enemy and must stop without attacking the enemy, moving at least their
        distance.  Charging may provoke a break test in opponents at the GM's discretion.
      </p>
    </abilitydescription>
    <abilitylevels>
      <abilitylevel>
        <levelnumber>0</levelnumber>
        <successes>2</successes>
        <attempts>1</attempts>
	<check>Resolve vs DDC 8</check>  
	<innate/>
     </abilitylevel>
      
      <abilitylevel>
        <levelnumber>1</levelnumber>
        <successes>3</successes>
        <attempts>1</attempts>
	<check>Resolve + 2 vs DDC 8</check>
      </abilitylevel>
      
      <abilitylevel>
        <levelnumber>2</levelnumber>
	<check>Resolve + 3 vs DDC 8</check>
      </abilitylevel>      
    </abilitylevels>
  </ability>


  

  <ability>
    <abilitytitle>Run</abilitytitle>
    <abilityid>physical.run</abilityid>
    <abilityclass>Melee</abilityclass>
    <keywords><physical/></keywords>
    <abilityattrmodifiers><attr>Speed</attr></abilityattrmodifiers>
    <abilitydescription>
      <p>
        The Run ability represents a double move.  It allows the character to move twice
	their movement rate during combat or pursuit.  This ability automatically succeeds
	if the character is not encapacicated in some way.
      </p>

      <p>
	In addition, the character may make a check to move a bit further in addition to their
	double move.  This skill represents the characters fleet footedness.  During combat
	this is represented by moving an extra 1-3 squares when playing on a grid, or something
	narrative in a TOTM combat.  During a pursuit the character increases their rank by
	two if they fail and three if they succeed.
      </p>      
    </abilitydescription>
    <abilitylevels>
      <abilitylevel>
        <levelnumber>0</levelnumber>
        <successes>1</successes>
        <attempts>1</attempts>
        <check>Std 2d8 vs DDC 10</check>
	<innate/>
      </abilitylevel>
      
      <abilitylevel>
        <levelnumber>1</levelnumber>
        <successes>3</successes>
        <attempts>1</attempts>
        <check>Std 2d8 + 1 vs DDC 10</check>
        <effect>
          As above.
        </effect>
      </abilitylevel>
      
      <abilitylevel>
        <levelnumber>2</levelnumber>
        <check>Std 2d8 + 2 vs DDC 10</check>
        <effect>
          As above.
        </effect>
      </abilitylevel>      
    </abilitylevels>
  </ability>


  <ability>
    <abilitytitle>Flee</abilitytitle>
    <abilityid>physical.flee</abilityid>
    <abilityclass>Immediate</abilityclass>
    <keywords><physical/></keywords>
    <abilityattrmodifiers><attr>Speed</attr></abilityattrmodifiers>
    <abilitydescription>
      <p>
        The Flee ability allows the character to move more than twice their movement rate
	away from an enemy, fear has given them wings.  Characters who are fleeing must
	make a Rally check in the End Stage to stop fleeing.  Characters may voluntarily
	flee if there exists a credible threat, or they may be forced to flee if they
	fail a break test.  For the purposes of game play fleeing is considered to be a
	double movement <emph>+d6</emph>.  Fleeing is successful if the character is not
	damaged in the following round.  Fleeing does <emph>not</emph> trigger an attack of
	opportunity.
      </p>
    </abilitydescription>
    <abilitylevels>
      <abilitylevel>
        <levelnumber>0</levelnumber>
        <successes>1</successes>
        <attempts>1</attempts>
        <check>Std Check vs DDC 12</check>	
	<innate/>
      </abilitylevel>
      
